[1] Cholera - Niger (Zinder)
Date: Wed, 27 Sep 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: African New Dimension [edited]
<http://www.andnetwork.com/index?service=direct/0/Home/recent.titleStory&sp=l52640>

Cholera has claimed 21 lives among 206 infected people in Niger
following seasonal rains that have flooded communities and left them
unable to cope with a health crisis.
A joint task force of the UN, Red Cross and Non Governmental
Organisations (NGOs) has been put in place to monitor the cholera
epidemic. Medecins sans Frontieres (MSF) is overseeing an isolation
unit 12 km south of the town Zinder, which is in the far southeast of
the country.
Niger health authorities said Zinder, 900 km east of the capital,
Niamey, was the worst affected. They said 8 people died and another
100 with symptoms of vomiting and diarrhea were taken to a regional
hospital center for treatment.
Landlocked Niger, hemmed in by the Sahara desert in north central
Africa, is the poorest country in the world, according to the UN's
Human Development Index (HDI), which ranks 177 countries according to
factors such as access to healthcare, literacy and life expectancy.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[A map of Niger can be found at:
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/niger.pdf>. The
state of Zinder can be found in the south, with north-central Nigeria
as Zinder's southern border. - Mod.LL]
