[4] Cholera - Nigeria (Sokoto)
Date: Mon, 25 Sep 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and Weekly Trust (Kaduna) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200609250560.html>

About 100 persons have died as a result of a cholera epidemic in 4
local government areas in Sokoto state recently. Weekly Trust reports
that many more people are still bed-ridden with the disease, fueling
fears that the last death has not been recorded yet.
The communicable disease, first detected in Tureta local government
about 50 km away from Sokoto, the state capital, claimed over 20
lives before another outbreak was recorded in Gwadabawa.
However, the outbreak in Dange-Shuni last week over shadowed the
number of causalities in Tureta, Gwadabawa and Wammako local
government areas all neighboring the state capital.
The outbreak in Shuni town and about 6 surrounding villages notably,
Kwannawa which is just behind, the Army Barracks, Sokoto was detected
on 21 Sep 2006 and within 48 hours, over 30 lives were lost while
about 158 victims were treated and discharged.
Although officials of the state ministry of health under the
leadership of the deputy director, Primary Health Care, Alhaji
Abubakar Khadi were not forthcoming with the exact figure of the
dead, officials of the Dange-Shuni local government council as 22 Sep
2006 put the figure at 22 while the state ministry insisted on 9 only.
However, the information officer of the Nigerian Red Cross Society in
Sokoto, Malam Ahmed Are Ashige told Weekly Trust that within the
initial 48 hours, about 9 deaths were recorded at the temporary
clinic set up at the Kwannawa Primary School just behind the Army
Barracks while over 22 people died in various villages surrounding Shuni town.
By Sun afternoon, 24 Sep 2006, the death toll rose to almost 40 with
about 200 of those affected treated and discharged while about 55
were still on admission.
[Byline: Aminu Mohammed]
